      "\n  have h2 : S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₂.toQuadSols.val := by\n    simpa using congr_arg (fun x => x.val) h\n  have h3 : S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₁.val := by\n    simp [Sols.toQuadSols]\n  have h4 : S₂.toQuadSols.val = S₂.val := by\n    simp [Sols.toQuadSols]\n  linarith [h2, h3, h4]\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that `S₁.cubicSol = S₂.cubicSol`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : S₁.cubicSol = S₂.cubicSol := by\n  have h3 : S₁.toQuadSols.quadSol = S₂.toQuadSols.quadSol := by\n    simpa using congr_arg (fun x => x.quadSol) h\n```\n\nWait, this is not quite right. `S₁.toQuadSols` is of type `QuadSols`, which is `structure QuadrSols (χ : ACCSystemQuad) extends χ.LinSols where quadSol : ∀ i : Fin χ.numberQuadratic, (χ.quadraticACCs i) val = 0`.\nSo `S₁.toQuadSols` has `val` (which is `S₁.val`) and `quadSol` (which is `S₁.toQuadSols.quadSol`).\nSimilarly for `S₂`.\n\nSo `h : S₁.toQuadSols = S₂.toQuadSols` implies `S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₂.toQuadSols.val` and `S₁.toQuadSols.quadSol = S₂.toQuadSols.quadSol`.\n\nLet's continue:\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : S₁.toQuadSols.cubicSol = S₂.toQuadSols.cubicSol := by\n  simpa using congr_arg (fun x => x.cubicSol) h\n```\n\nWait, `toQuadSols` is a coercion from `Sols` to `QuadSols`, so `S₁.toQuadSols` is of type `QuadSols`.\n`QuadSols` does not have a `cubicSol` field. `Sols` does. So this approach is incorrect.\n\nInstead, we need to look at the definition of `Sols` and `toQuadSols`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : S₁.val = S₂.val := by\n  have h3 : S₁.toQuadSols = S₂.toQuadSols := h\n  have h4 : S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₁.val := by\n    simp [Sols.toQuadSols]\n  have h5 : S₂.toQuadSols.val = S₂.val := by\n    simp [Sols.toQuadSols]\n  have h6 : S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₂.toQuadSols.val := by\n    rw [h3]\n```\n\nSo we have `S₁.toQuadSols.val = S₂.toQuadSols.val`, which by `h4` and `h5` means `S₁.val = S₂.val`.\n\nNow for the cubic part. Since `S₁` and `S₂` are both `Sols`, they already have `cubicSol` fields. The equality `↑S₁ = ↑S₂` means that the `toQuadSols` 